node.text:
Jump into a first-person view of airborne operations as @4_25Spartans #paratroopers conducted a joint operations at Donnelly Drop Zone, #Alaska during exercise Red Flag 21-2, June 17. 

The Spartan Brigade is the only #airborne infantry brigade combat team in the #Arctic and #Pacific theaters, providing the unique capability to project an expeditionary force by #air. 

(Video by Maj. Jason Welch, 4th BCT, 25th Inf. Div.; Photos courtesy of Sheila de Vara, 673rd Public Affairs)

node.title: Spartan Paratroopers jump into Red Flag

node.text:
Tomorrow is Flag Day!

The first celebration of the U.S. Flag's birthday was held in 1877 on the 100th anniversary of the Flag Resolution of 1777. However, it is believed that the first annual recognition of the flag's birthday dates back to 1885 when school teacher, BJ Cigrand, first organized a group of Wisconsin school children to observe June 14 - the 108th anniversary of the official adoption of The Stars and Stripes as the Flag's Birthday. Cigrand, now known as the 'Father of Flag Day,' continued to publically advocate the observance of June 14 as the flag's 'birthday', or 'Flag Day' for years.

The use of “Taps” is unique to the United States military, as the call is sounded at funerals, wreath-laying ceremonies and memorial services. 

“Taps” originally began as a signal to extinguish lights. 

Today, it is sounded as the final call every evening on military installations & military funerals as well as its formal recognition as our “National Song of Remembrance.”

#ArmyTeam | #ArmyHistory
